Urka Sren and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, a company creating stylish health-focused smart products for women. Bellabeat empowers women by collecting data on activity, sleep, and stress, providing them with valuable insights into their health and habits. Since 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly, offering a range of products available through online retailers and their website. While Bellabeat utilizes traditional advertising, their primary focus is digital marketing. This includes Google Search optimization, active social media presence (Facebook, Instagram, Twitter), engaging video ads on Youtube, and targeted display ads on the Google Display Network.

Bellabeat, a leading women's health and wellness company, leverages technology to empower its users. Their stylish smart wearables track a range of health metrics, including:

  • Physical Activity: Track steps, distance, and overall activity levels.
  • Sleep Patterns: Gain insights into sleep quality, duration, and sleep stages.
  • Stress and Heart Rate: Monitor stress levels and heart rate to understand overall well-being.

By collecting and analyzing this data, Bellabeat empowers women to gain valuable knowledge about their health and make informed lifestyle choices.

ASK¶

Project Objectives and Stakeholders¶

Goal: Grow Bellabeat's market share and position within the smart device industry.

Objectives:¶

  • Identify key user behavior trends through data analysis.
  • Leverage these trends to refine and optimize Bellabeat's marketing strategies.

Stakeholders:¶

  • Urka Sren (Co-founder & Chief Creative Officer): Oversees Bellabeat's creative direction and will be interested in user insights informing future product design and features.
  • Sando Mur (Co-founder & Executive Team): With his expertise in mathematics, Mur will value data-driven insights for strategic decision making.
  • Bellabeat Marketing Analytics Team: Responsible for utilizing data analysis to guide and improve marketing strategies. They will directly utilize the insights gleaned from this project.

Data Preparation¶

Source:¶

  • Open-source "FitBit Fitness Tracker Data" from Kaggle.
  • Data represents activity information from Fitbit users who consented to share their data.

Limitations:¶

  • Age: Data collection occurred in 2016, potentially limiting its relevance to current trends.
  • Sample Size: The dataset is relatively small, consisting of only 30 users, which might impact the generalizability of insights.

Data Considerations:¶

  • Reliability: Due to the small sample size, findings may not be statistically significant and cannot be considered entirely reliable.
  • Originality: The data is obtained from a third-party source (Kaggle).
  • Currency: The data is not current, reflecting user activity patterns from 2016.
  • Citation: As the data is from a third-party source, citation information is likely unavailable.

Tools:¶

  • Python for data cleaning, processing, transformation, and visualization.

Leveraging Python Libraries:¶

This project will utilize Python's powerful data analysis libraries to uncover user behavior trends:

  • NumPy: Provides the foundation for numerical computations and array manipulations, essential for handling user activity data.
  • Pandas: Offers high-performance data structures (DataFrames) for efficient data organization, cleaning, and analysis.
  • Matplotlib: A versatile library for creating various visualizations (charts, graphs) to explore trends and patterns in user activity.
  • (Optional) Scikit-learn: If the data allows, this library might be used for more advanced analysis techniques like machine learning to uncover deeper user behavior insights.

These libraries work together seamlessly to streamline data manipulation, analysis, and visualization, enabling us to extract meaningful insights from the user activity data.

# Data Type Conversion
minutes_intensities_df['ActivityMinute'] = pd.to_datetime(minutes_intensities_df['Id,ActivityMinute,Intensity'].str.split(',').str[1])
minutes_mets_df['ActivityMinute'] = pd.to_datetime(minutes_mets_df['Id,ActivityMinute,METs'].str.split(',').str[1])
minute_sleep_df[['Id', 'ActivityMinute', 'Value', 'LogId']] = minute_sleep_df['Id,date,value,logId'].str.split(',', expand=True)
minute_sleep_df['ActivityMinute'] = pd.to_datetime(minute_sleep_df['ActivityMinute'])
weight_log_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(weight_log_df['Date'])

# Splitting Columns
minutes_intensities_df[['Id', 'ActivityMinute', 'Intensity']] = minutes_intensities_df['Id,ActivityMinute,Intensity'].str.split(',', expand=True)
minutes_mets_df[['Id', 'ActivityMinute', 'METs']] = minutes_mets_df['Id,ActivityMinute,METs'].str.split(',', expand=True)

# Handling Missing Values
weight_log_df['Fat'].fillna(weight_log_df['Fat'].mean(), inplace=True)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the Minute Steps Data into a DataFrame
minute_steps_df = pd.read_csv("minuteStepsNarrow_merged_cleaned.csv")

# Convert 'ActivityMinute' to datetime
minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'] = pd.to_datetime(minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'])

# Aggregate steps data to calculate total steps per day
steps_per_day = minute_steps_df.groupby(minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'].dt.date)['Steps'].sum()

# Create a line plot to visualize total steps over time
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(steps_per_day.index, steps_per_day.values, marker='o', linestyle='-')
plt.title('Total Steps Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Total Steps')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load the cleaned CSV file containing step data
minute_steps_df = pd.read_csv("minuteStepsNarrow_merged_cleaned.csv")

# Convert 'ActivityMinute' column to datetime type
minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'] = pd.to_datetime(minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'])

# Extract day of the week from 'ActivityMinute'
minute_steps_df['DayOfWeek'] = minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'].dt.day_name()

# Aggregate step counts by day of the week
steps_by_day = minute_steps_df.groupby('DayOfWeek')['Steps'].sum().reset_index()

# Define the order of days for plotting
days_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']

# Plot the bar graph
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
bars = plt.bar(steps_by_day['DayOfWeek'], steps_by_day['Steps'], color='lightgrey')  # Change color to lightgrey

# Add labels to the bars
for bar in bars:
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_height(), str(int(bar.get_height())), 
             ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)

# Add grid
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Set plot title and labels
plt.title('Total Steps by Day of the Week', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Day of the Week', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Steps', fontsize=12)

# Set the order of x-axis ticks
plt.xticks(steps_by_day['DayOfWeek'], days_order)

# Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Show plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Load the cleaned CSV file containing step data
minute_steps_df = pd.read_csv("minuteStepsNarrow_merged_cleaned.csv")

# Convert 'ActivityMinute' column to datetime type
minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'] = pd.to_datetime(minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'])

# Extract day of the week from 'ActivityMinute'
minute_steps_df['DayOfWeek'] = minute_steps_df['ActivityMinute'].dt.day_name()

# Aggregate step counts by day of the week
steps_by_day = minute_steps_df.groupby('DayOfWeek')['Steps'].sum().reset_index()

# Define the order of days for plotting
days_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']

# Create a gradient color scheme
colors = plt.cm.viridis(np.linspace(0, 1, len(steps_by_day)))

# Plot the line chart with points
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for i, day in enumerate(days_order):
    day_index = steps_by_day[steps_by_day['DayOfWeek'] == day].index[0]
    plt.plot([day_index, day_index], [0, steps_by_day.loc[day_index, 'Steps']], color=colors[i], linestyle='-', linewidth=3, marker='o', markersize=8)

# Add labels to the points
for i, steps in enumerate(steps_by_day['Steps']):
    plt.text(i, steps, str(int(steps)), ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)

# Add grid
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Set plot title and labels
plt.title('Total Steps by Day of the Week', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Day of the Week', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Steps', fontsize=12)

# Set the order of x-axis ticks and labels
plt.xticks(range(len(days_order)), days_order)

# Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Show plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.font_manager as fm

# Set the style
sns.set_style("whitegrid")

# Group data by 'ActivityDay' and sum the 'StepTotal' and 'Calories' for each day
daily_steps_calories = daily_steps_df.groupby('ActivityDay')['StepTotal'].sum().reset_index()
daily_steps_calories['Calories'] = daily_calories_df.groupby('ActivityDay')['Calories'].sum().values

# Find the Fraunces font
fraunces_font = fm.findfont(fm.FontProperties(family='Fraunces'))

# Set the font properties
fraunces_prop = fm.FontProperties(fname=fraunces_font)

# Plot total steps vs calories
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Plot total steps
plt.plot(daily_steps_calories['ActivityDay'], daily_steps_calories['StepTotal'], label='Total Steps', color='cornflowerblue', linewidth=2)

# Plot calories
plt.plot(daily_steps_calories['ActivityDay'], daily_steps_calories['Calories'], label='Calories Burned', color='salmon', linewidth=2)

# Add labels and title with Fraunces font
plt.xlabel('Date', fontsize=14, fontproperties=fraunces_prop)
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14, fontproperties=fraunces_prop)
plt.title('Total Steps vs Calories Burned', fontsize=16, fontproperties=fraunces_prop)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12, fontproperties=fraunces_prop)
plt.legend(fontsize=12, prop=fraunces_prop)

# Add grid lines
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Add annotations
for i, day in enumerate(daily_steps_calories['ActivityDay']):
    if i % 7 == 0:  # Annotate every week
        plt.text(day, daily_steps_calories['StepTotal'][i], f"{daily_steps_calories['StepTotal'][i]:,}", ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10, color='cornflowerblue')
        plt.text(day, daily_steps_calories['Calories'][i], f"{daily_steps_calories['Calories'][i]:,}", ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10, color='salmon')

# Show plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Define colors
colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728']

# Calculate total minutes for each activity type
sedentary_minutes = daily_intensities_df['SedentaryMinutes'].sum()
lightly_active_minutes = daily_intensities_df['LightlyActiveMinutes'].sum()
fairly_active_minutes = daily_intensities_df['FairlyActiveMinutes'].sum()
very_active_minutes = daily_intensities_df['VeryActiveMinutes'].sum()

# Create a pie chart
labels = ['Sedentary', 'Lightly Active', 'Fairly Active', 'Very Active']
sizes = [sedentary_minutes, lightly_active_minutes, fairly_active_minutes, very_active_minutes]
explode = (0.05, 0.15, 0.20, 0.15)  # explode all slices slightly
shadow = True

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
wedges, texts, autotexts = plt.pie(sizes, explode=explode, labels=None, colors=colors, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140, shadow=shadow, textprops={'fontsize': 12, 'fontname': 'Fraunces'})
plt.setp(autotexts, size=12, weight="bold", fontname='Fraunces')  # Increase font size and weight for autopct text

# Move figures outside of the pie chart
for text in texts:
    text.set_horizontalalignment('center')  # Center align labels
for autotext in autotexts:
    autotext.set_horizontalalignment('center')  # Center align autopct figures
    autotext.set_color('black')  # Set autopct figures color to black

plt.title('Distribution of Activity Types', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', fontname='Fraunces')

# Add legend for activity types
plt.legend(labels=labels, loc='upper right', fontsize=12, title='Activity Types', title_fontsize='14')

plt.axis('equal')  # Equal aspect ratio ensures that pie is drawn as a circle.
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Convert 'ActivityHour' to datetime type
hourly_steps_df['ActivityHour'] = pd.to_datetime(hourly_steps_df['ActivityHour'])

# Group the data by hour and calculate the mean steps
hourly_steps_mean = hourly_steps_df.groupby(hourly_steps_df['ActivityHour'].dt.hour)['StepTotal'].mean()

# Create a color gradient for the bars (grey shades)
colors = plt.cm.Greys(np.linspace(0.2, 1, len(hourly_steps_mean)))

# Plot the hourly steps as vertical bars
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
bars = plt.bar(hourly_steps_mean.index, hourly_steps_mean.values, color=colors)

# Add labels and annotations to the bars
for bar in bars:
    height = bar.get_height()
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, height, f'{int(height)}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10, color='black')
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, height * 0.5, f'{int(height)}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=8, color='white')

plt.title('Hourly Average Steps', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Hour of the Day', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Average Steps', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 24), fontsize=10)  # Set x-ticks to display all 24 hours
plt.yticks(fontsize=10)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Read the data from CSV files
daily_steps_df = pd.read_csv("dailySteps_merged.csv")
daily_calories_df = pd.read_csv("dailyCalories_merged.csv")

# Convert 'ActivityDay' to datetime type
daily_steps_df['ActivityDay'] = pd.to_datetime(daily_steps_df['ActivityDay'])
daily_calories_df['ActivityDay'] = pd.to_datetime(daily_calories_df['ActivityDay'])

# Aggregate daily data to weekly data
weekly_steps_df = daily_steps_df.resample('W-Mon', on='ActivityDay').sum().reset_index()
weekly_calories_df = daily_calories_df.resample('W-Mon', on='ActivityDay').sum().reset_index()

# Combine steps and calories data into a single DataFrame
weekly_trends_df = pd.merge(weekly_steps_df, weekly_calories_df, on='ActivityDay')

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Plot weekly steps
plt.plot(weekly_trends_df['ActivityDay'], weekly_trends_df['StepTotal'], label='Weekly Steps', color='blue', marker='o')

# Plot weekly calories burned
plt.plot(weekly_trends_df['ActivityDay'], weekly_trends_df['Calories'], label='Weekly Calories Burned', color='orange', marker='o')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Week', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Weekly Trends: Steps vs Calories Burned', fontsize=16)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)

# Add grid lines
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Show plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
